  "course_description": "",
  "course_notes": "This course introduces students to the historical study of borders and border regions in Central and Eastern European history from the 17th to the 21st century. The focus allows for reflection on concepts such as sovereignty, territoriality, and the rise of modern (nation) states. Readings address examples such as Central and Eastern European (Germany, Poland, western borderlands of Russian Empire and USSR, today's Ukraine) as well as Central Asian (Kazakhstan). Wars, revolutions, shattered empires and new border regimes (such as the EU) have frequently redrawn European borders, making this world region an apt location for the subject. Students will be able to adapt their final projects in this class to geographic regions of their choice.",
